<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="12">Discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="12">
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C1E91261-79E3-423B-80B6-F9B448760C86" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis intermedius Chu 1982:430 [Engl. p. 437]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="intermedius">Pseudecheneis intermedius Chu, 1982</taxonomicName>
is here considered a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:31513E00-E57B-4618-A71C-41681FF7E329" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis paviei Vaillant 1892:126 [2]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="paviei">P. paviei</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C1E91261-79E3-423B-80B6-F9B448760C86" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis intermedius Chu 1982:430 [Engl. p. 437]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="intermedius">Pseudecheneis intermedius</taxonomicName>
was distinguished from 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:31513E00-E57B-4618-A71C-41681FF7E329" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis paviei Vaillant 1892:126 [2]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="paviei">P. paviei</taxonomicName>
by the relative position of the adipose and anal fins (Chu, 1982). Our examination of material identified as 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C1E91261-79E3-423B-80B6-F9B448760C86" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis intermedius Chu 1982:430 [Engl. p. 437]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="intermedius">P. intermedius</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:31513E00-E57B-4618-A71C-41681FF7E329" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis paviei Vaillant 1892:126 [2]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="paviei">P. paviei</taxonomicName>
from northern Vietnam and southern China revealed no significant differences in the relative position of the adipose and anal fins, nor could we find any other morphological or biometric differences to distinguish between the two. Chu et al. (1990) indicated that the outline of the snout tip can be used to distinguish between the two species, but this is a variable character that changes with the position of the maxillary barbels (i.e. whether they are projected sideways or pressed against the head) and is therefore not considered a useful diagnostic feature here. We tentatively follow Zhou &amp; Chu (1992) in considering 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:DB70F0B4-4FB7-4148-A6B4-CC37F69F7DF1" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis tchangi Hora 1937:348" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tchangi">P. tchangi (Hora, 1937)</taxonomicName>
a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sulcata">P. sulcata</taxonomicName>
. The status of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:DB70F0B4-4FB7-4148-A6B4-CC37F69F7DF1" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis tchangi Hora 1937:348" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tchangi">P. tchangi</taxonomicName>
is being investigated in a separate study by HHN.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="13">
The relative height of the neural spines readily distinguishes 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:175A3E4F-DFFE-405A-A858-8920376B267D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis serracula Ng &amp; Edds 2005" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="serracula">P. serracula</taxonomicName>
from its congeners, especially 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sulcata">P. sulcata</taxonomicName>
(which occurs sympatrically and syntopically with it; see below). The difference is readily apparent in radiographs (Fig. 5), but even without recourse to such techniques, it is possible to see a difference in external morphology caused by the difference in height of the neural spines. The increase in body depth in the region between the dorsal and adipose fins caused by the neural spines in 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:175A3E4F-DFFE-405A-A858-8920376B267D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis serracula Ng &amp; Edds 2005" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="serracula">P. serracula</taxonomicName>
imparts a somewhat hunched appearance compared to 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sulcata">P. sulcata</taxonomicName>
(compare Figs. 3 and 6).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="13">
Biplots of the length of the adipose-fin base for 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:175A3E4F-DFFE-405A-A858-8920376B267D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis serracula Ng &amp; Edds 2005" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="serracula">P. serracula</taxonomicName>
vs. 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sulcata">P. sulcata</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 7) and caudal peduncle depth against SL for 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C280D1E1-5F99-419A-94EC-8709045672E0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis crassicauda Ng &amp; Edds 2005" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="crassicauda">P. crassicauda</taxonomicName>
vs. 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:175A3E4F-DFFE-405A-A858-8920376B267D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis serracula Ng &amp; Edds 2005" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="serracula">P. serracula</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sulcata">P. sulcata</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 8) show that the regression lines are significantly different (ANCOVA; P&lt;0.05). Likewise, biplots of eye diameter against SL for for 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C280D1E1-5F99-419A-94EC-8709045672E0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis crassicauda Ng &amp; Edds 2005" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="crassicauda">P. crassicauda</taxonomicName>
vs. 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:175A3E4F-DFFE-405A-A858-8920376B267D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis serracula Ng &amp; Edds 2005" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="serracula">P. serracula</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sulcata">P. sulcata</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 9) are also significantly different (ANCOVA; P&lt;0.05).
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageNumber="15" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:175A3E4F-DFFE-405A-A858-8920376B267D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis serracula Ng &amp; Edds 2005" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="serracula">Pseudecheneis serracula</taxonomicName>
was found syntopically with 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sulcata">P. sulcata</taxonomicName>
in the Seti River (the differences among the three species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:0A1502AF-3B84-4BA1-95C1-C24D72CCC5EE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis Blyth 1860:154" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudecheneis</taxonomicName>
known from the Ganges River drainage are highlighted in Table 3). Sisorid congeners occurring syntopically have been noted in several genera, e.g. 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:188E1893-9C92-49FC-9F84-1B096BA2C562" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Bagarius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Bagarius Bleeker 1854:121" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Bagarius</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:FA21FA6F-AC80-43FF-ABE5-FE7A17E958A2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Gagata" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gagata Bleeker 1858:204, 206" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gagata</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C4304186-4FD4-4672-BDF1-AC51D2C01419" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Glyptothorax Blyth 1860:154" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Glyptothorax</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F461FB4B-8C79-4B5C-8C7F-E115BD79B6AE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Nangra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Nangra Day 1877:493" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Nangra</taxonomicName>
(DeWitt, 1960; Roberts, 1983; Edds, 1993; Roberts &amp; Ferraris, 1998). It is common to find coexisting mixed-species groups of related fishes (Matthews, 1998), although hypotheses of resource partitioning (e.g. Zaret &amp; Rand, 1971; Werner et al, 1977) would predict otherwise. Matthews (1998) suggested that fishes in heterospecific schools may gain information or other benefits. Such groupings might increase foraging efficiency or enhance detection and avoidance of predators (Boucher et al., 1982; Allan, 1986; Allan and Pitcher, 1986; Pitcher, 1986). Gorman (1988) reported feeding associations between two species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:D94C8C47-A4DF-4C1E-8D24-0036F11FAFCF" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Notropis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Notropis Rafinesque 1818:204" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Notropis</taxonomicName>
(Cyprinidae), and Greenberg (1991) noted similar interactions among three species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:581B2792-A5D8-4F1A-9029-65BAD4C03674" class="Actinopterygii" family="Percidae" genus="Percina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Percina Perca Haldeman 1842:330" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Percina</taxonomicName>
(Percidae). Mendelson (1975) concluded that multispecific schooling by four species of cyprinids might gain them anti-predator benefit. Moyle &amp; Li (1979) and Allan (1986) suggested that rare fish species might benefit by hiding in groups of one or more other species that were more abundant. A few fishes enter into more complex symbioses via nest associations, some of which may be mutualistic (Matthews, 1998).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="16">
It is possible that the material we identify as 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sulcata">P. sulcata</taxonomicName>
from the Seti River is not conspecific with 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sulcata">P. sulcata</taxonomicName>
s. str., given that 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:0A1502AF-3B84-4BA1-95C1-C24D72CCC5EE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis Blyth 1860:154" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudecheneis</taxonomicName>
species appear to have restricted distributions (they are not found below elevations of ca. 150 m asl) and that the type locality of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sulcata">P. sulcata</taxonomicName>
is in the tributaries of the Brahmaputra River in the Khasi Hills, India, a considerable distance to the southeast. A separate study by HHN is examining variation in 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sulcata">P. sulcata</taxonomicName>
throughout its range, and will include a redescription of the species and discussion of its diagnostic characters.
</paragraph>
